 historically focused on these strong, highly relatable emotional expressions, while niche emotions like `fear` or `surprise` remain at a flat, low baseline.\r\n* **Market Fluctuation and Timeline Continuity**: A sharp, synchronized drop across all curves occurs around 2021, followed by a noticeable recovery leading into 2024. This trend points to potential changes in data tracking or platform aggregation methods during that period. Most importantly, because corrupted dates and formatting errors were resolved in the query (`release_year >= 1970`), the X-axis presents a continuous and clear timeline without any missing years or alignment issues.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T19:53:55+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h3>4.2 Historical Trends of Music Emotion Dimensions (Line Chart)</h3>\n<p>This line chart tracks the annual volume of tracks associated with different emotional categories from 1970 to 2024:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Growth in Track Volume</strong>: The chart shows a steady and gradual increase in the number of tracks across all main emotional categories from 1970 through the late 2000s, followed by a sharp rise that peaks around 2017–2018. This peak reflects the rapid growth of digital music catalogs driven by the expansion of modern music streaming platforms.</li>\n<li><strong>Prevalence of Core Emotions</strong>: Emotional categories such as <code>joy</code> (dark blue line), <code>sadness</code> (light blue line), and <code>anger</code> (orange line) consistently maintain the highest positions throughout the timeline. This steady pattern indicates that mainstream music production has historically focused on these strong, highly relatable emotional expressions, while niche emotions like <code>fear</code> or <code>surprise</code> remain at a flat, low baseline.</li>\n<li><strong>Market Fluctuation and Timeline Continuity</strong>: A sharp, synchronized drop across all curves occurs around 2021, followed by a noticeable recovery leading into 2024. This trend points to potential changes in data tracking or platform aggregation methods during that period. Most importantly, because corrupted dates and formatting errors were resolved in the query (<code>release_year &gt;= 1970</code>), the X-axis presents a continuous and clear timeline without any missing years or alignment issues.</li>\n</ul>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782330102367_-1916350637","id":"20260624-194142_1727861451","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T19:41:42+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T19:53:55+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T19:53:55+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15557"},{"text":"%jdbc(hive)\r\n-- Analytical Scenario 3: Compute micro-level intra-genre track popularity rankings using analytical window functions\r\nWITH RankedTracks AS (\r\n    SELECT \r\n        genre,\r\n        release_year,\r\n        artist,\r\n        song,\r\n        popularity,\r\n        DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY genre ORDER BY popularity DESC) AS intra_genre_rank\r\n    FROM default.spotify_cleaned\r\n    WHERE release_year >= 2010\r\n)\r\nSELECT \r\n    genre,\r\n    intra_genre_rank,\r\n    release_year,\r\n    artist,\r\n    song,\r\n    popularity\r\nFROM RankedTracks\r\nWHERE intra_genre_rank <= 3\r\nORDER BY genre ASC, intra_genre_rank ASC;","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T19:49:52+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{"0":{"graph":{"mode":"multiBarChart","height":653.797,"optionOpen":true,"setting":{"multiBarChart":{"stacked":true},"stackedAreaChart":{}},"commonSetting":{},"keys":[{"name":"genre","index":0,"aggr":"sum"}],"groups":[{"name":"genre","index":0,"aggr":"sum"}],"values":[{"name":"popularity","index":5,"aggr":"su