n### 4.4 Correlation Between Audio Loudness and Track Popularity (Scatter Plot)\r\n\r\nThis scatter plot analyzes how track popularity correlates with physical audio loudness (grouped into 1 dB buckets) across various musical genres:\r\n\r\n* **Non-linear Relationship**: The distribution of data points shows that songs with extremely low loudness (between -30 dB and -15 dB) generally maintain lower popularity scores, mostly staying under 40. As loudness increases toward the -10 dB to -4 dB range, the density of points shifts upward, with more tracks reaching higher popularity levels.\r\n* **Diminishing Returns at High Loudness**: When the loudness levels approach or exceed the -2 dB to 0 dB threshold, the upward trend levels off, and the average popularity marks begin to spread out or decline slightly. This supports the idea that while a certain level of volume helps a track stand out, excessive loudness compression does not guarantee higher audience engagement.\r\n* **Effect of Data Bucketing**: Grouping the continuous loudness values using `CAST(loudness AS INT)` allows the scatter plot to display clear vertical clusters on the X-axis. This structure makes it easier to spot how different genres (represented by different colored dots) perform at identical loudness baselines without cluttering the visualization.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T19:56:31+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h3>4.4 Correlation Between Audio Loudness and Track Popularity (Scatter Plot)</h3>\n<p>This scatter plot analyzes how track popularity correlates with physical audio loudness (grouped into 1 dB buckets) across various musical genres:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Non-linear Relationship</strong>: The distribution of data points shows that songs with extremely low loudness (between -30 dB and -15 dB) generally maintain lower popularity scores, mostly staying under 40. As loudness increases toward the -10 dB to -4 dB range, the density of points shifts upward, with more tracks reaching higher popularity levels.</li>\n<li><strong>Diminishing Returns at High Loudness</strong>: When the loudness levels approach or exceed the -2 dB to 0 dB threshold, the upward trend levels off, and the average popularity marks begin to spread out or decline slightly. This supports the idea that while a certain level of volume helps a track stand out, excessive loudness compression does not guarantee higher audience engagement.</li>\n<li><strong>Effect of Data Bucketing</strong>: Grouping the continuous loudness values using <code>CAST(loudness AS INT)</code> allows the scatter plot to display clear vertical clusters on the X-axis. This structure makes it easier to spot how different genres (represented by different colored dots) perform at identical loudness baselines without cluttering the visualization.</li>\n</ul>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782330979592_-1484642113","id":"20260624-195619_785786698","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T19:56:19+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T19:56:31+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T19:56:31+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15561"},{"text":"%jdbc(hive)\r\n\r\n-- Analytical Scenario 5: Execute multi-dimensional OLAP drill-down analysis within the dominant market genre\r\nSELECT \r\n    emotion,\r\n    COUNT(1) AS track_volume,\r\n    ROUND(AVG(popularity), 2) AS avg_popularity\r\nFROM default.spotify_cleaned\r\nWHERE genre = 'RAP'\r\n  AND emotion IS NOT NULL\r\nGROUP BY emotion\r\nORDER BY track_volume DESC;","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T19:58:04+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{"0":{"graph":{"mode":"pieChart","height":300,"optionOpen":true,"setting":{"pieChart":{}},"commonSetting":{},"keys":[{"name":"emotion","index":0,"aggr":"sum"}],"groups":[],"values":[{"name":"track_volume","index":1,"aggr":"sum"}]},"helium":{}}},"editorSetting":{"language":"sql","editOnDblClick":false},"editorMode":"ace/mode/sql"},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"TABLE","data":"emotion\ttrack_volume\tavg_popularity\nanger\t12625\t42.05\njoy\t11467\t42.12\nsadness\t6386\t42.08\nfear\t1234\t41.38\nlove\t1031\t42.84\nsurprise\t252\t41.25\ntrue\t1\t59.0\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782311181322_1279640669","id":"20260624-142621_1076805905","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T14:26:21+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T14:39:33+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T14:39:40+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15562"},{"text":"%md\r\n### 4.5 Distribution of Psychological Emotions Within the RAP Genre (Pie Chart)\r\n\r\nThis pie chart details the composition of tracks across different emotional labels specifically within the `RAP` genre, following an OLAP drill-down query:\r\n\r\n* **Concentration in Two Major Emotions**: The chart shows that two emotional categories, `anger` (medium blue sector) and `joy` (light blue sector), together account for the vast majority of the track volume within this genre. This distribution suggests that the content ecosystem of this style heavily concentrates on these two strong emotional expressions.\r\n* **Proportion of Secondary and Niche Sentiments**: In comparison, emotional categories like `sadness` (orange sector), `fear` (peach sector), and `love` (green sector) occupy much smaller shares of the total volume. This distribution demonstrates that while diverse moods exist, they remain secondary to the dominant emotional themes of the genre.\r\n* **Validation of Data Cleaning and Sub-setting**: The visualization effectively excludes incomplete data entries by using the condition `AND emotion IS NOT NULL` in the query. This ensures that the percentage breakdown inside the pie slices represents only valid records, providing a clear insight into the genre's internal thematic structure.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T19:59:09+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h3>4.5 Distribution of Psychological Emotions Within the RAP Genre (Pie Chart)</h3>\n<p>This pie chart details the composition of tracks across different emotional labels specifically within the <code>RAP</code> genre, following an OLAP drill-down query:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Concentration in Two Major Emotions</strong>: The chart shows that two emotional categories, <code>anger</code> (medium blue sector) and <code>joy</code> (light blue sector), together account for the vast majority of the track volume within this genre. This distribution suggests that the content ecosystem of this style heavily concentrates on these two strong emotional expressions.</li>\n<li><strong>Proportion of Secondary and Niche Sentiments</strong>: In comparison, emotional categories like <code>sadness</code> (orange sector), <code>fear</code> (peach sector), and <code>love</code> (green sector) occupy much smaller shares of the total volume. This distribution demonstrates that while diverse moods exist, they remain secondary to the dominant emotional themes of the genre.</li>\n<li><strong>Validation of Data Cleaning and Sub-setting</strong>: The visualization effectively excludes incomplete data entries by using the condition <code>AND emotion IS NOT NULL</code> in the query. This ensures that the percentage breakdown inside the pie slices represents only valid records, providing a clear insight into the genre's internal thematic structure.</li>\n</ul>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782331107161_-91250163","id":"20260624-195827_2071759107","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T19:58:27+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T19:59:09+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T19:59:09+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15563"},{"text":"%md\r\n# 5. Insights and Explanations\r\n\r\nBy cleaning the data and analyzing it across five different scenarios, we have resolved major data quality issues and identified several clear trends in streaming consumption and music production. The core industry insights from this project are detailed below:\r\n\r\n### 5.1 Market Prominence of Mainstream Genres and Competitive Saturation\r\nThe general market analysis shows that genres like `POP`, `ROCK`, and `RAP` lead significantly in both overall track count and average audience popularity. This pattern indicates that streaming consumption remains highly focused on a few major genres. Furthermore, using the window function to analyze the top 3 tracks within these dominant genres reveals that the popularity scores between the first, second, and third-ranked songs are very close, with differences often under 1.5%. From a business perspective, this shows that competition at the top of mainstream genres is highly saturated, making it difficult for new releases to capture a significant share of audience attention.\r\n\r\n### 5.2 Historical Loudness Trends and the Limits of Volume Amplification\r\nThe analysis connecting acoustic loudness with song popularity provides clear evidence of historical production shifts. Since the 1970s, across major emotional categories like joy, sadness, and anger, the average mixing loudness has steadily increased closer to the 0 dB limit. This supports the well-known industry trend often called the \"Loudness War,\" where production teams increase overall volume and use dynamic compression to help tracks stand out immediately in modern playlists.\r\nHowever, the scatter plot reveals that this trend has clear limits. Once the average loudness crosses a threshold of around -4 dB, track popularity stops rising and begins to decline. This suggests that excessive volume amplification reduces the dynamic range and depth of the audio, which can lead to listener fatigue and lower long-term replay rates on streaming platforms.\r\n\r\n### 5.3 Emotional Composition Within the RAP Genre\r\nBy performing a targeted drill-down analysis on the highly popular `RAP` genre, we can better understand the emotional themes behind its market performance. The data indicates that the genre relies heavily on two primary emotional categories: `anger` and `joy`. Together, these two intense emotional states account for over 70% of the total track volume within the genre. This combination of high-energy expression and upbeat themes represents a major defining characteristic of modern rap music, allowing it to maintain strong audience engagement and adapt well across different market segments.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T20:02:11+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h1>5. Insights and Explanations</h1>\n<p>By cleaning the data and analyzing it across five different scenarios, we have resolved major data quality issues and identified several clear trends in streaming consumption and music production. The core industry insights from this project are detailed below:</p>\n<h3>5.1 Market Prominence of Mainstream Genres and Competitive Saturation</h3>\n<p>The general market analysis shows that genres like <code>POP</code>, <code>ROCK</code>, and <code>RAP</code> lead significantly in both overall track count and average audience popularity. This pattern indicates that streaming consumption remains highly focused on a few major genres. Furthermore, using the window function to analyze the top 3 tracks within these dominant genres reveals that the popularity scores between the first, second, and third-ranked songs are very close, with differences often under 1.5%. From a business perspective, this shows that competition at the top of mainstream genres is highly saturated, making it difficult for new releases to capture a significant share of audience attention.</p>\n<h3>5.2 Historical Loudness Trends and the Limits of Volume Amplification</h3>\n<p>The analysis connecting acoustic loudness with song popularity provides clear evidence of historical production shifts. Since the 1970s, across major emotional categories like joy, sadness, and anger, the average mixing loudness has steadily increased closer to the 0 dB limit. This supports the well-known industry trend often called the &ldquo;Loudness War,&rdquo; where production teams increase overall volume and use dynamic compression to help tracks stand out immediately in modern playlists.\n<br  />However, the scatter plot reveals that this trend has clear limits. Once the average loudness crosses a threshold of around -4 dB, track popularity stops rising and begins to decline. This suggests that excessive volume amplification reduces the dynamic range and depth of the audio, which can lead to listener fatigue and lower long-term replay rates on streaming platforms.</p>\n<h3>5.3 Emotional Composition Within the RAP Genre</h3>\n<p>By performing a targeted drill-down analysis on the highly popular <code>RAP</code> genre, we can better understand the emotional themes behind its market performance. The data indicates that the genre relies heavily on two primary emotional categories: <code>anger</code> and <code>joy</code>. Together, these two intense emotional states account for over 70% of the total track volume within the genre. This combination of high-energy expression and upbeat themes represents a major defining characteristic of modern rap music, allowing it to maintain strong audience engagement and adapt well across different market segments.</p>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782311972793_-1717807195","id":"20260624-143932_805260235","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T14:39:32+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T20:02:11+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T20:02:11+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15564"},{"text":"%md\r\n# 6. Recommendations\r\n\r\nBased on the data trends identified across the different analysis scenarios, the following three practical recommendations are proposed to help streaming platforms and music production labels improve their business decisions and technical setup:\r\n\r\n### 6.1 Production Level: Applying Standardized Loudness Controls over Excessive Compression\r\nThe scatter plot analysis showing a downward trend at high volume levels indicates that music labels and mixing engineers should avoid the continuous practice of simply boosting overall volume. Streaming platforms are encouraged to consistently apply standardized **loudness normalization features** that keep playback volume around a stable, balanced level, such as **-8 dB to -5 dB**. This approach ensures a much more comfortable listening experience, helping to prevent listener fatigue and naturally encouraging users to stay longer on the platform.\r\n\r\n### 6.2 Operation Level: Enhancing Recommendations by Integrating Emotion Categories with Music Genres\r\nMany streaming recommendation systems currently focus mainly on general music genres. However, our drill-down analysis shows that even within a single major genre, tracks can express very different emotional moods. Additionally, less common emotional themes like `love` and `surprise` maintain steady popularity scores despite their low song counts. Therefore, platforms should update their recommendation models to better identify and include these emotional moods alongside traditional genres. By connecting music suggestions to the user’s immediate mood, platforms can introduce high-value niche songs to relevant audiences, helping smaller tracks gain visibility while giving the platform a unique competitive edge.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T20:03:36+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h1>6. Recommendations</h1>\n<p>Based on the data trends identified across the different analysis scenarios, the following three practical recommendations are proposed to help streaming platforms and music production labels improve their business decisions and technical setup:</p>\n<h3>6.1 Production Level: Applying Standardized Loudness Controls over Excessive Compression</h3>\n<p>The scatter plot analysis showing a downward trend at high volume levels indicates that music labels and mixing engineers should avoid the continuous practice of simply boosting overall volume. Streaming platforms are encouraged to consistently apply standardized <strong>loudness normalization features</strong> that keep playback volume around a stable, balanced level, such as <strong>-8 dB to -5 dB</strong>. This approach ensures a much more comfortable listening experience, helping to prevent listener fatigue and naturally encouraging users to stay longer on the platform.</p>\n<h3>6.2 Operation Level: Enhancing Recommendations by Integrating Emotion Categories with Music Genres</h3>\n<p>Many streaming recommendation systems currently focus mainly on general music genres. However, our drill-down analysis shows that even within a single major genre, tracks can express very different emotional moods. Additionally, less common emotional themes like <code>love</code> and <code>surprise</code> maintain steady popularity scores despite their low song counts. Therefore, platforms should update their recommendation models to better identify and include these emotional moods alongside traditional genres. By connecting music suggestions to the user’s immediate mood, platforms can introduce high-value niche songs to relevant audiences, helping smaller tracks gain visibility while giving the platform a unique competitive edge.</p>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782315670974_775623947","id":"20260624-154110_1716359093","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T15:41:10+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T20:03:36+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T20:03:36+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15565"},{"text":"%md\r\n# 7. Conclusion\r\n\r\nThis project implemented a digital music data management and multi-dimensional analysis workflow using Apache Hadoop, Apache Hive, and Apache Zeppelin.\r\n\r\nThe work began by addressing common data quality issues in the raw dataset, including incorrect string formatting, missing fields, and misaligned columns. By using regular expressions and explicit data type casting (`CAST`), basic data cleaning and normalization were completed at the storage layer. On top of this clean dataset, the project used analytical tools such as window functions, data bucketing, and OLAP drill-down queries to find correlations across different variables. Finally, these results were converted into clear, interactive dashboards using Zeppelin's built-in visualization engines.\r\n\r\nBy examining how different musical traits relate to popularity trends, this study analyzed the market presence of major genres, the historical changes in music loudness, and the emotional themes within specific music styles. These findings allowed us to propose practical recommendations for loudness standards and recommendation algorithms. Overall, this project demonstrates how structured data engineering and analysis can effectively turn raw logs into useful industry insights, providing valuable hands-on experience with big data architectures and visualization workflows.","user":"anonymous","dateUpdated":"2026-06-24T20:10:44+0000","config":{"colWidth":12,"enabled":true,"results":{},"editorSetting":{"language":"markdown","editOnDblClick":true},"editorMode":"ace/mode/markdown","editorHide":true,"tableHide":false},"settings":{"params":{},"forms":{}},"results":{"code":"SUCCESS","msg":[{"type":"HTML","data":"<h1>7. Conclusion</h1>\n<p>This project implemented a digital music data management and multi-dimensional analysis workflow using Apache Hadoop, Apache Hive, and Apache Zeppelin.</p>\n<p>The work began by addressing common data quality issues in the raw dataset, including incorrect string formatting, missing fields, and misaligned columns. By using regular expressions and explicit data type casting (<code>CAST</code>), basic data cleaning and normalization were completed at the storage layer. On top of this clean dataset, the project used analytical tools such as window functions, data bucketing, and OLAP drill-down queries to find correlations across different variables. Finally, these results were converted into clear, interactive dashboards using Zeppelin's built-in visualization engines.</p>\n<p>By examining how different musical traits relate to popularity trends, this study analyzed the market presence of major genres, the historical changes in music loudness, and the emotional themes within specific music styles. These findings allowed us to propose practical recommendations for loudness standards and recommendation algorithms. Overall, this project demonstrates how structured data engineering and analysis can effectively turn raw logs into useful industry insights, providing valuable hands-on experience with big data architectures and visualization workflows.</p>\n"}]},"apps":[],"jobName":"paragraph_1782315767588_-1505446657","id":"20260624-154247_41010533","dateCreated":"2026-06-24T15:42:47+0000","dateStarted":"2026-06-24T20:10:44+0000","dateFinished":"2026-06-24T20:10:44+0000","status":"FINISHED","progressUpdateIntervalMs":500,"$$hashKey":"object:15566"},{"text":"","u